# Scroll Lock for Overlays

When creating modals, dropdowns, menus, or any overlay UI that covers part of the screen:

**Always lock body scroll** to prevent the main page from scrolling behind the overlay.

## How to Implement

Use the `useBodyScrollLock` hook:

```tsx
import { useBodyScrollLock } from '../../hooks/useBodyScrollLock'

// For modals (always lock when mounted)
function MyModal({ onClose }) {
  useBodyScrollLock(true)
  return <div className="fixed inset-0">...</div>
}

// For toggleable dropdowns (lock only when open)
function MyDropdown() {
  const [open, setOpen] = useState(false)
  useBodyScrollLock(open)
  return <div>...</div>
}
```

## Components That Already Have Scroll Lock

- `AppModal` - base modal component (has it built-in)
- `AppSidebar` - hamburger menu
- `WelcomeModal` - onboarding modal
- `LocationModal` in MiningSection

## Header Dropdowns — Do NOT Lock Body Scroll

Small header dropdowns (`AppUserMenu`, `AppNotificationBell`) use a click-away backdrop but **must not** call `useBodyScrollLock`. Locking body scroll adds `padding-right` to compensate for the hidden scrollbar, which shifts the fixed header and makes the right side jump. Use `overscroll-contain` on the dropdown panel instead.

## Don't Forget

If you create a **full-screen or centered modal** with `fixed inset-0`, add scroll lock. Lightweight header dropdowns are the exception above.
